ce:section.ce:para:
Upon the addition of Fe(III) and Hg(II) ions, the PL emission intensity of PN-CQDs decreases. Stern-Volmer plot (Fig. 7(b & d)) shows a linear decline, indicating a straightforward relationship between quencher concentration and quenching efficiency. The linear Stern-Volmer plot suggests a static quenching mechanism, where metal ions interact with PN-CQDs to form ground-state complexes which are non-fluorescent. Time-resolved PL data given by Fig. 8
                        (a) shows no significant change in the PL lifetime (details given in Table 2
                        ) of PN-CQDs in the presence of Fe(III) and Hg(II) ions. The unchanged PL lifetime further supports static quenching, where quenching occurs due to complex formation rather than collisional quenching that would alter the excited-state lifetime. Further, the zeta potential (Fig. 8(b)) of PN-CQDs changes from −12.45 mV to −2.94 mV (with Fe(III)) and −2.24 mV (with Hg(II)). The reduction in the negative zeta potential indicates that the positively charged metal ions are binding to the surface of PN-CQDs, neutralizing the surface charge. The reduction in zeta potential implies decreased electrostatic repulsion, which may lead to aggregation or clustering of PN-CQDs. This binding supports the formation of ground-state complexes leading to static quenching. Also, binding reduces the number of PN-CQDs available to emit fluorescence, leading to a decrease in PL intensity.
